(44, 17, 22, 44, 19, 35, 35, 'too superstitious', 'Worship and Superstition Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of worship, with Paul addressing the superstitious nature of the Athenians and the town clerk referencing the worship of Diana in Ephesus. This connection highlights the cultural context of idolatry in both cities.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 22, 24, 10, 2, 3, 'too superstitious', 'Superstition and Heathen Practices', 'This connection highlights the theme of superstition and vain customs. Both passages address the folly of worshiping created things, with Paul noting the Athenians'' superstitions and Jeremiah warning against the customs of the heathen.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 22, 24, 50, 38, 38, 'too superstitious', 'Idolatry and Superstition Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of idolatry, as both passages address the folly of worshiping false images and idols. Paul refers to the Athenians as ''too superstitious,'' paralleling Jeremiah''s description of a land consumed by ''graven images'' and idol worship.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 23, 43, 4, 22, 22, NULL, 'Worship of the Unknown God', 'This connection highlights the theme of worshiping without full understanding. Both passages emphasize the idea of worshiping what is not fully known, with Acts referencing the ''UNKNOWN GOD'' and John stating, ''Ye worship ye know not what.''', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 23, 48, 4, 8, 9, NULL, 'Worship of Unknown God', 'This connection highlights the theme of ignorance in worship. Both passages address the idea of serving false gods and the transition to knowing the true God.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 23, 43, 17, 3, 3, 'TO THE UNKNOWN GOD', 'Knowledge of the True God', 'This connection highlights the theme of knowing God. In Acts, Paul refers to the ''unknown God'' that the Athenians worship, while in John, eternal life is defined as knowing the ''only true God.'' Both passages emphasize the importance of recognizing and understanding God''s true nature.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 23, 44, 17, 30, 30, 'ignorantly worship', 'Ignorance and Divine Command', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ignorance in worship. The first passage identifies the worship of the ''UNKNOWN GOD,'' while the second addresses God''s response to such ignorance, commanding repentance.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 23, 46, 1, 21, 21, 'UNKNOWN GOD', 'Wisdom and Ignorance in Worship', 'This connection highlights the theme of ignorance in worship and the role of divine wisdom. In Acts, the ''UNKNOWN GOD'' represents the world''s failure to recognize God, while in 1 Corinthians, it states that ''the world by wisdom knew not God.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 23, 53, 2, 4, 4, 'whom therefore ye ignorantly worship', 'Worship of the Unknown God', 'This connection highlights the theme of worship, as both passages address the concept of what is worshipped and the nature of divinity. Acts 17:23 mentions the worship of an ''Unknown God,'' while 2 Thessalonians 2:4 discusses one who exalts himself as God, indicating a contrast in understanding divine authority.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 23, 45, 1, 28, 28, NULL, 'Knowledge of God and Worship', 'This connection highlights the theme of knowledge of God and the consequences of ignoring it. In Acts, the worship of the ''UNKNOWN GOD'' reflects a lack of true understanding, while Romans discusses the rejection of God in knowledge leading to a reprobate mind.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 24, 11, 8, 27, 27, 'dwelleth not in temples made with hands', 'God''s Presence Beyond Temples', 'Both passages emphasize that God cannot be contained within physical structures. Acts 17:24 states that God ''dwelleth not in temples made with hands,'' while 1 Kings 8:27 questions if God can dwell on earth, noting that even the heavens cannot contain Him.', 'theme', 0.685, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 17, 24, 5, 10, 14, 14, 'Lord of heaven and earth', 'God''s Sovereignty Over Creation', 'Both passages emphasize God''s ownership of the earth and heavens. Acts 17:24 states that God is Lord of heaven and earth, while Deuteronomy 10:14 affirms that the heaven and the earth belong to the Lord.', 'theme', 0.5449999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
